data.content:
Two separate issues:

### Case 1: `left && right` with `dynamic`

The `&&` operator desugars into `operator false(x) ? x : operator &(x, y)`. It requires **three** things on the left operand's type: `operator true`, `operator false`, **and** `operator &`.

`IFilter` defines `true`/`false` but **no `operator &`**. In earlier C# versions, having `dynamic` on the right caused the entire expression to be dynamically bound, so the compiler skipped static validation of the left operand's operators. C# 15 tightens this: it now **statically validates** the left operand's operators for `&&`/`||` even when the right operand is `dynamic`. Since `IFilter` lacks `operator &`, it's rejected at compile time.

**Fix** — add the missing operator to the interface:
```csharp
interface IFilter
{
    static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y) => x;
    static bool operator true(IFilter x) => true;
    static bool operator false(IFilter x) => false;
}
```
Or cast `left` to `CompositeFilter` (which has all three operators), or avoid `dynamic`.

---

### Case 2: `ref readonly` returning lambda → CS0518

`CS0518` means *"Predefined type '…' is not defined or imported"*. The compiler needs to synthesize an anonymous delegate type with a `ref readonly` return, and that requires a BCL type (likely a new attribute or delegate infrastructure type) that isn't present in your targeting pack.

This is almost certainly an **SDK/runtime version mismatch** — your C# 15 compiler is ahead of the runtime libraries you're targeting. Make sure your .NET 11 SDK preview and targeting pack are the same version. Check the full CS0518 message for the exact missing type.

**Workaround** — use a named delegate or method instead of the lambda:
```csharp
delegate ref readonly int RefReadonlyFunc();

static ref readonly int GetValue() => ref value;
RefReadonlyFunc fn = GetValue;
```
